@node Copyright "ImGauge Documentation - Copyright"

@{b}ImGauge@{ub} was written with the idea to do a program that is useful,
reliable, fast and doesn't crash. Let's call this software quality.

Developing software of a good quality can take more than ten times the
work than writing rubbish. This means, even if a program appears to be
short, there can be @{i}lots@{ui} of work in it.

If you like and use this software, please send 10 DM to @{"me" link Author}.

@{b}ImGauge@{ub} may be included in Fred Fish's AmigaLib and on the AmiNet.

@{b}IT IS STRICTLY PROHIBITED TO SELL THIS SOFTWARE ON MEDIA OTHER THAN
THOSE COMING DIRECTLY FROM THE SOURCES DESCRIBED ABOVE. THIRD PARTIES
NEED THE WRITTEN PERMISSION OF THE AUTHOR.@{ub}

@{b}IT IS ALSO STRICTLY PROHIBITED TO USE AND/OR REUSE PARTS OR ROUTINES
OF THE PROGRAM AND DOCUMENTATION WITHOUT THE WRITTEN PERMISSION OF THE
AUTHOR.@{ub}

If you @{u}don't understand@{uu} or @{u}don't accept@{uu} the contents of
this page, you're not allowed to run @{b}ImGauge@{ub} or store it on any
media. You must delete it @{b}@{u}NOW@{ub}@{uu}.

@endnode

@node Introduction "ImGauge Documentation - Introduction"
Raytracing has become very popular in the computer community. A famous
raytracer is Imagine, which is my favourite one.

The graphical user interface of Imagine has not improved as fast as the
Amiga's GUI. Most people can live with it, but I couldn't live with the
missing percentage gauge as a rendering display, which is a must if you
want to develop software conform to the @{"User Interface Style Guide" link styleguide} .
Imagine still uses @{i}topaz.font@{ui} as its default font, and if you want to see
Imagine's rendering status, you must go near your monitor and decipher the
small letters in the title bar.

This was @{u}no@{uu} sollution for me.

So I coded a program with a scalable @{"SCALAR ®" link scalar} GUI that is completely
system- and Style Guide conform and doesn't eat up lots of CPU cycles.
@{b}ImGauge@{ub} doesn't patch anything and makes no illegal stuff.

@{b}ImGauge@{ub} will sit in it's place and wait for Imagine. When Imagine is
loaded, @{b}ImGauge@{ub} starts to examine Imagine and display it's status. @{b}ImGauge@{ub}
currently uses an interval of 1 secs between 2 checks which is enough and
doesn't hurt the system performance. Out of that, @{b}ImGauge@{ub} tries
to display the time Imagine is already rendering and the expected total time.

Out of that, @{b}ImGauge@{ub} offers the option to alter the task priority of Imagine
to you. This is useful if Imagine is rendering and some software requires
to multitask at a low priority (i.e. SAS/C running always at priority -1).
@{b}ImGauge@{ub} will never blow itself out of the water, it sets its own
priority always equal to Imagine's priority or, if Imagine's priority is
less than zero, to zero. The priority can only be changed in the interval
from -3 to 3 to avoid conflicts with the system software.

Special care has been taken to make all GUI functions compatible to
@{b}3rd party graphics boards@{ub}. If you discover any problems,
please @{"report" link Bugreport} them to me.

Created using SAS/C 6.56.

@endnode


@node Usage "ImGauge Documentation - Usage"

@{b}ImGauge@{ub} should be used from the Workbench. If you use it from the Shell,
you don't have to opportunity to specify any options.

When run from the Workbench, you can alter some options of @{b}ImGauge@{ub} by
changing the tooltypes of its icon.

@{b}PUBSCREEN=<pubscreen name>@{ub}

This tooltype specifies the name of the public screen to open on.
Usually this is "Workbench", which is the default.

@{b}FONTNAME=<fontname>@{ub}

This tooltype specifies the name of the font to use. The font must have the
ending ".font". You can use fixed-width and proportional fonts.

If @{b}ImGauge@{ub} can't open your font, it will fall back to "topaz.font", size 8.

@{b}FONTSIZE=<font size>@{ub}

This tooltype specifies the size of the desired font. @{b}ImGauge@{ub} will only
accept fonts with a size greater or equal to 5.

@endnode


